Phillippe, Pierre, Raoul, Yvan, Yves.","French (<b>Brûlé</b>):","topographic name for someone living in a place cleared for use by burning, from <i>brûlé</i> ‘burnt’ (Old French <i>bruslé</i>, past participle of <i>brusler</i> ‘to burn’). Some instances of the name may derive from the same word used with reference to disfigurement by burning, either accidentally or as a medieval ordeal or punishment."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bruley was born in 1348, in Waterstock, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Bruley II, was 44 and his mother, Bona FitzEllis, was 38. He married Agnes Bruley in 1374, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1436, in his hometown, at the age of 88."},"et":{"1348–1436":"1348–1436","1360–1383":"1360–1383","1377–Female":"1377–Surnud","1379–1446":"1379–1446","1383–1423":"1383–1423","1305–1372":"1305–1372","1310–1375":"1310–1375","1374":"1374","Abt 1379":"umbes 1379","Bef 1423":"enne 1423","Abt 1346":"umbes 1346","1372":"1372","1383":"1383","19 January 1375":"19. jaanuar 1375","1360":"1360","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","Bef 1372":"enne 1372","Abt 1383":"umbes 1383","1436":"1436","1446":"1446",